      <format>text/x-wiki</format>
      <text bytes="8214" xml:space="preserve">{{short description|General dislike of humanity}}
{{Redirect|Misanthrope|the Molière comedy|Le Misanthrope|the French metal band|Misanthrope (band)|the album by American hard rock band DED|Mis.an.thrope}}
[[File:LeMisanthrope.jpg|thumb|''[[The Misanthrope|Le Misantrope]]'', 1719 ad.]]
'''Misanthropy''' is the general [[hatred]], dislike, [[distrust]] or [[contempt]] of the [[human species]], [[human behavior]] or [[human nature]]. A '''misanthrope''' or '''misanthropist''' is someone who holds such views or feelings. The word's origin is from the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] words [[wikt:μῖσος|μῖσος]] (''mīsos'', &quot;hatred&quot;) and [[wikt:ἄνθρωπος|ἄνθρωπος]] (''ānthropos'', &quot;man, human&quot;). The condition is often confused with [[asociality]].

== Western culture ==
=== Arts ===
[[Gustave Flaubert]] once declared that he would &quot;die of suppressed rage at the folly of [his] fellow men.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vFzQdS8N_5IC&amp;pg=PR14|title=The Letters of Gustave Flaubert: 1857-1880|page=xiv|publisher=Harvard University Press|date=1982|isbn=0674526406}}&lt;/ref&gt; Misanthropy has also been ascribed to a number of writers of satire, such as [[William S. Gilbert]] (&quot;I hate my fellow-man&quot;) and [[William Shakespeare]] (''[[Timon of Athens]]''). [[Jonathan Swift]] is widely believed to have been misanthropic (see ''[[A Tale of a Tub]]'' and, most especially, Book IV of ''[[Gulliver's Travels]]''). Poet [[Philip Larkin]] has been described as a misanthrope.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books-mr-miseryguts-philip-larkins-letters-show-all-the-grim-humour-that-was-a-hallmark-of-his-great-1558190.html|title=Books: Mr Miseryguts: Philip Larkin's letters show all the grim humor that was a hallmark of his great poems, but, as the years pass, they also chart the true depths of his misanthropy and despair|last=Raban|first=Jonathan|newspaper=The Independent|date=October 17, 1992|accessdate=June 18, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Molière]]'s play ''[[The Misanthrope]]'' is one of the more famous French plays on this topic. Less famous, but more contemporary is the 1971 play by Françoise Dorin, ''Un sale égoïste'' (A Filthy Egoist) which takes the point of view of the misanthrope and entices the viewer to understand his motives.

[[Michelangelo]] has been called a misanthrope.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1bALBwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA211|title=Art, Myth and Deviance|page=211|last=Shoham|first=Shlomo Giora|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|date=2008|isbn=978-1443802970}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Don Van Vliet]] (commonly known as Captain Beefheart) has been described as a misanthrope, with close friend [[Kristine McKenna]] stating that he &quot;thought human beings were the worst species that was ever dreamed up&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/dec/18/local/la-me-captain-beefheart-20101218/2|title=Don Van Vliet dies at 69; avant-garde rock musician known as Captain Beefheart|last=Cromelin|first=Richard|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 18, 2010|accessdate=June 18, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Philosophy ===
The [[Pre-Socratic philosophy|pre-Socratic philosopher]] [[Heraclitus]] was by various accounts a misanthrope and a loner who had little patience for human society.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=https://www.ancient.eu/Heraclitus_of_Ephesos/|title=Heraclitus_of_Ephesus|work=Ancient History Encyclopedia|access-date=2017-12-08}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=Death by philosophy : the biographical tradition in the life and death of the archaic philosophers Empedocles, Heraclitus, and Democritus|last=1953-|first=Chitwood, Ava|date=2004|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=0472113887|location=Ann Arbor|pages=80|oclc=54988783}}&lt;/ref&gt; In a fragment, the philosopher complained that &quot;people [were] forever without understanding&quot; of what was, in his view, the nature of reality.

In Western philosophy, misanthropy has been connected to [[social isolation|isolation from human society]]. In [[Plato]]'s ''[[Phaedo]]'', [[Socrates]] describes a misanthrope in relation to his fellow man: &quot;Misanthropy develops when without art one puts complete trust in somebody thinking the man absolutely true and sound and reliable and then a little later ''discovers'' him to be bad and unreliable ... and when it happens to someone often ... he ends up ... hating everyone.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| last=Stern| first=Paul| title=Socratic Rationalism and Political Philosophy: An Interpretation of Plato's Phaedo| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nJAFnvm2fg4C| year=1993| publisher=SUNY Press| isbn=978-0-7914-1573-3| page=94}}&lt;/ref&gt; Misanthropy, then, is presented as a potential result of thwarted expectations or even excessively naïve optimism, since Plato argues that &quot;art&quot; would have allowed the potential misanthrope to recognize that the majority of men are to be found in between good and evil.&lt;ref&gt;Stern 95.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Aristotle]] follows a more [[Ontology|ontological]] route: the misanthrope, as an essentially [[solitude|solitary]] man, is not a man at all: he must be a beast or a god, a view reflected in the [[Renaissance]] view of misanthropy as a &quot;beast-like state&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| last=Jowett| first=John| title=The Oxford Shakespeare: The Life of Timon of Athens| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gHTKzYKrh6wC| year=2004| publisher=Oxford UP| isbn=978-0-19-281497-5| page=29}}&lt;/ref&gt;

There is a difference between [[philosophical pessimism]] and misanthropy. [[Immanuel Kant]] said that &quot;Of the crooked timber of humanity, no straight thing can ever be made&quot;, and yet this was not an expression of the uselessness of mankind itself. Kant further stated that hatred of mankind can take two distinctive forms: aversion from men ([[anthropophobia]]) and enmity towards them.&lt;ref name=&quot;kant191&quot;&gt;{{cite book| author=Immanuel Kant| title=Lectures on Ethics| date=2001-03-19| publisher=Cambridge University Press| isbn=978-0-521-78804-5| page=191}}&lt;/ref&gt; The condition can arise partly from dislike and partly from ill-will.&lt;ref name=&quot;kant191&quot;/&gt;

[[Martin Heidegger]] has also been said&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=Reading Heidegger's Black Notebooks 1931-1941|publisher=|others=Farin, Ingo,, Malpas, Jeff|isbn=0262034018|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|pages=321|oclc=926820993|last1 = Farin|first1 = Ingo|last2 = Malpas|first2 = Jeff|date = 2016-02-19}}&lt;/ref&gt; to show misanthropy in his concern of the &quot;they&quot;—the tendency of people to conform to one view, which no one has really thought through, but is just followed because, &quot;they say so&quot;. This might be thought of as more a criticism of [[conformity]] than of people in general. Unlike [[Arthur Schopenhauer|Schopenhauer]], Heidegger was opposed to any systematic ethics; however, in some of his later thought, he does see the possibility of harmony between people, as part of the four-fold, mortals, gods, earth, and sky.

== Middle Eastern thought ==

In the [[Judeo-Islamic philosophies (800–1400)]], the [[Jewish philosophy|Jewish philosopher]], [[Saadia Gaon]], uses the [[Platonism|Platonic]] idea that the self-isolated man is dehumanized by friendlessness to argue against the misanthropy of [[anchorite]] [[asceticism]] and [[Recluse|reclusiveness]].&lt;ref&gt;{{citation|title=Jewish and Islamic Philosophy: Crosspollinations in the Classic Age|first=Lenn Evan|last=Goodman|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|year=1999|isbn=0748612777|pages=25–6}}&lt;/ref&gt;

