'''Pope Paul II''' ({{lang-la|Paulus II}}; 23 February 1417 – 26 July 1471),&lt;ref name=&quot;Papi&quot;&gt;{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/paolo-ii_(Enciclopedia-dei-Papi)/ |title=PAOLO II |first=Anna |last=Modigliani |encyclopedia=Enciclopedia dei Papi |language=it |year=2000}}&lt;/ref&gt; born '''Pietro Barbo''', was head of the [[Catholic Church]] and ruler of the [[Papal States]] 
from 30 August 1464 to his death in 1471. When his maternal uncle [[Eugene IV]] became [[pope]], Barbo switched from training to be a merchant to religious studies. His rise in the Church was relatively rapid. Elected pope in 1464, Paul amassed a great collection of art and antiquities.

==Early life==

Pietro Barbo was born in [[Venice]], the son of Niccolo and Polixena Condulmer Barbo.&lt;ref name=Weber&gt;[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11578a.htm Weber, Nicholas. &quot;Pope Paul II.&quot; The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 15 May 2020. {{PD-notice}}&lt;/ref&gt; His mother was the sister of [[Pope Eugenius IV]] (1431–1447). Through his father he was a member of the noble [[Barbo von Waxenstein (family)|Barbo family]]. His adoption of the spiritual career, after having been trained as a merchant, was prompted by his uncle's election as pope. His consequent promotion was rapid. He became Archdeacon of Bologna, and Bishop of Cervia and of Vicenza, and in 1440 became a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal-deacon]].&lt;ref name=WeberAttribution/&gt; Barbo gained popularity through his generosity. He boasted that if elected pope he would buy each cardinal a villa to escape the summer heat.&lt;ref name=&quot;D'Elia&quot;&gt;{{cite book|first=Anthony |last=D'Elia|title=A sudden terror: The plot to kill a renaissance pope|publisher=Harvard|year=2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;{{page needed|date=February 2020}}

After having been [[lay abbot]] of [[Santa Maria in Sylvis]] since 1441, in 1445 he succeeded [[Giuliano Cesarini]] as archpriest of the [[Vatican Basilica]]. Barbo was very influential under Eugene IV, [[Pope Nicholas V|Nicholas V]], and Calixtus III, but less so under Pius II.&lt;ref name=WeberAttribution/&gt; Barbo had a marked propensity to enjoy dressing up in sumptuous ecclesiastical finery.
